General Statistics & Data Quality¶

Thus, we can see that our dataset is a list of dictionaries, of which each is a single recipe. The dictionary itself consists of text fields that are all either filled with a string or None, if they are empty.

Due to a previously unknown error during scraping (as it has not produced an error message in its log), some values of 96,036 recipes could not be recorded correctly. Unfortunately, this error has been recognised too late, which is why those entries will be missing in all six datasets.

These 96,036 recipes without date also lack values in the other fields. Due to this reason, those recipes need to be removed from the dataset completely. Unfortunately, we are forced to reduce the dataset by almost a third because of this. However, we can gather some statistics before dropping the affected entries:

In [9]:
# Splitting the date and creating new columns for year, month and day
# and cleaning some other values:

def clean_dataset(data):
    date = []
    errors = []
    for i, r in enumerate(data):
        date = data[i]['date'].split('.')
        data[i]['printed'] = data[i]['printed'].split('(')[0].replace('.','')
        data[i]['saved'] = data[i]['saved'].split('(')[0].replace('.','')
        data[i]['shared'] = data[i]['shared'].split('(')[0].replace('.','')

        # For all complete recipes, produce date features
        try:
            data[i]['year'] = date[2]
            data[i]['month'] = date[1]
            data[i]['day'] = date[0]

        # For all others, set dirty values to None
        except IndexError:
            errors.append(i)
            data[i]['date'] = None
            data[i]['printed'] = None
            data[i]['saved'] = None
            data[i]['shared'] = None
            data[i]['number_ratings'] = 0

    print(len(errors))
    
clean_dataset(chefkoch)

Missing values¶

Almost all columns/attributes have a value in every recipe (data point), but some columns like subtitle, time_hrs, time_mins and user are only filled partly. More specifically, while user is only empty in 1.5% of the data points, subtitle and time_mins are empty in approximately half of the cases and time_hrs is merely provided for 917 of 413,769 recipes, which is only 0.22% of the data. Thus, the column time_hrs is useless for further analysis.

Dirty data¶

For further analysis, we can now drop the recipes with wrong data entries (which have been replaced by None above).

After handling the missing values, we need to check if the available data is actually correct, i.e. if all numeric fields like rating or number of clicks actually contain numeric values.

These attributes require intensive cleaning before their numerical values can be used for analysis. However, knowing the duration of a recipe or the amount of calories might only provide limited benefit for the analysis. Additionally, the calories are only provided for 10% of all recipes, as 202,082 entries contain "keineAngabe", which means that no value has been provided.

The column user_activity shows that 69,819 users have provided zero contributions, even though they are part of this dataset, because they have published at least one recipe. This means that user_activity does not provide reliable information, as it might neglect recipe that have been published before a certain date, for example.

The attribute user_date, however, might be useful, as it can be cleaned and converted quite easily and can show us how many users have joined chefkoch at a certain point of time.

Thus, there is not much use for the columns 'calories' and the three time values, because their data quality is too low. They can be dropped:

In [31]:
chefdf = chefdf.drop(['calories', 'time_cook', 'time_rest', 'time_work', 'user_activity'], axis=1)

# Convert user_date
def convert_userdate(x):
    x = x.split(' ')[2]
    return x

chefdf['user_date'] = pd.to_datetime(chefdf['user_date'].apply(convert_userdate))

Users¶

What can we learn about the users of this website? Main questions are:

  • Which users have contributed the largest number of recipes?
  • Which users are the most successful/efficient?
  • Which recipes have made these users so successful?

From a business perspective, we want to find the users that have published successful recipes consistently, as they would be a valuable source for selecting recipes to feature in our service.

Creating the features¶

For the analysis in this section, we will create a separate DataFrame for performing the necessary operations. In the following, we will pursue multiple steps to create an informative overview on the most active users of this platform.

  • Add the count of recipes for each user:
In [35]:
# Show users with most contribution in terms of recipe count
recipe_count = pd.DataFrame(chefdf['user'].value_counts())
recipe_count.columns = ['recipe_count']
  • How many prints, ratings, shares and saves has each user "collected" with his/her recipes in total?
In [36]:
# Add sum of metrics per user
printed = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'printed'])
printed = printed.groupby('user').sum()
topusers = recipe_count.join(printed)
In [37]:
# Add sum of metrics per user
rated = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'number_ratings'])
rated = rated.groupby('user').sum()
topusers = topusers.join(rated)
In [38]:
# Add sum of metrics per user
saved = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'saved'])
saved = saved.groupby('user').sum()
topusers = topusers.join(saved)
In [39]:
# Add sum of metrics per user
shared = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'shared'])
shared = shared.groupby('user').sum()
topusers = topusers.join(shared)
  • What is each users' average rating?
In [40]:
# What is the average recipe rating per user?
rating = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'avg_rating'])
rating = rating.groupby('user').mean()
topusers = topusers.join(rating)
  • What is the median (average) rating for each user? (This is interesting, as the median is much more robust regarding outliers)
In [41]:
# The median rating could also be interesting, 
#  as it is more robust than the average regarding outliers
median_rating = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'avg_rating'])
median_rating = median_rating.groupby('user').median()

# need to rename the columns before joining
median_rating.columns = ['median_rating']  
topusers = topusers.join(median_rating)

We should also consider the fact that all of these attributes accumulate over time. For this purpose, we should add another feature that shows have passed since the user published his/her first recipe on the platform.

  • For how many days has each user been active?
In [42]:
# For how long has a user been active
days = pd.DataFrame(chefdf, columns=['user', 'user_date'])
days = days.groupby('user').min()  # shows the earliest publication date per user
In [43]:
# We can write a function for calculating the number of days between two dates
from datetime import datetime
end = chefdf['date'].max()  # Consider the latest recipe date as "today"
def days_passed(d1):
    return abs((end - d1).days)  # returns the number of days only
In [44]:
# Now we calculate the days that have passed since then:  
days['days'] = days['user_date'].apply(days_passed)
days = days.drop(['user_date'], axis=1)

# Adding this to the topusers dataframe:
topusers = topusers.join(days)

Based on these attributes, we can now calculate further metrics that help understanding the dataset better. For example: the average prints per recipe and the ratio between number of ratings and number of recipes for each user.

However, not all possible combinations of attributes might be useful, which is why we will not explore all of them.

In [45]:
# Average number of ratings per recipe
topusers['ratings_per_recipe'] = topusers['number_ratings'] / topusers['recipe_count']

We want to avoid divisions of or by zero, which would lead to NaN or infinite values.

# How many prints per recipe? (printing seems to be the most popular way of appreciation)
topusers['prints_per_recipe'] = topusers['printed'] / (topusers['recipe_count']+1)

The histograms show a high skewness in most attributes (number_ratings, saved, shared, printed, recipe_count). This means that there is a very large number of users that contribute only a few recipes or have collected only a few ratings/prints/etc, which is why the data is strongly skewed with regards to these attributes. At the same time, there is a small number of users that is highly active, publishing many recipes and collecting many ratings. This can be seen in the large difference between 75% percentile and maximum for these attributes.

We can see that more than 75% of all users have received an average rating of 3.2 stars (out of 5), but not a single user has received the maximum rating of 5 stars, which provides us with a rather balanced distribution. The attributes recipe_count, clicks_per_recipe and number_votes show their skewness in the differences between mean and median (or between 75% percentile and maximum). Still, these attributes could be used for further insights, as they are not capped like avg_rating.

An approach of handling the skewness could be to transform and normalise the data fields by using a logarithmic transformation and then shifting the mean to zero to achieve a certain degree of normalisation. Normal in this case means that a distributions skewness and kurtosis move towards those of a normal distribution. Unfortunately, transformations can strongly reduce the interpretability of attributes, as the more these values are transformed, the further away they are from their easy-to-understand real value, which a reader can relate to.

Correlations¶

In the next step, we can build a scatter matrix to see how these features that we have just created:

In [55]:
from pandas.plotting import scatter_matrix
_ = scatter_matrix(vote_efficiency, alpha=0.2, figsize=(15, 15), diagonal='kde')

The scatter matrix shows pairwise distributions and provides information about each attribute's distribution. The diagonal of the matrix shows the Kernel Density Estimates, which are estimates for each attribute's probability density. This can be used to identify the distribution of each attribute. We can see that actually all attributes have a more or less exponential distribution.

We can see that there seems to be a high correlation between the pair combinations of printed, number_ratings, saved and shared. The dependencies between avg_rating and median_rating, as well as recipes per month and recipe count are understandable, as those attribute pairs are closely related.

To analyse the dependencies in more detail, we can use a correlation coefficient to measure linear dependency between two attributes. The package scipy provides multiple functions for this purpose. We can start by using the Pearson's r, which is the most commonly used correlation coefficient:

In [56]:
# Compute all Pearson r's and their p-Value, which are then stored in lists:
from scipy.stats.stats import pearsonr

def calculate_pearson(df):
    pear = []
    pearp = []
    for i in df:
        pear_i = []
        pearp_i = []
        for j in df:
            pear_i.append(pearsonr(df[i], df[j])[0])
            pearp_i.append(pearsonr(df[i], df[j])[1])
        pear.append(pear_i)
        pearp.append(pearp_i)
    return pear, pearp

The pairwise correlations can confirm the assumptions we have taken from the scatter matrix above. It is quite interesting that avg/median rating and days do not seem to correlate with any of the popularity metrics.

It has to be noted that the Pearson r assumes normal distribution and only measure linear dependence between values. To achieve a more general view, we should calculate a different correlation coefficient for comparison: The Spearman's rho, which is a rank correlation coefficient, does measure how well the relationship between two attributes can be described with a monotonic function. This includes linear functions, but is not limited to them. (An alternative option to this would be Kendall's tau, which operates in a similar way.)

The evaluation with Spearman's rho confirms the correlations that were found with Pearson's r and even increases their value. However, some coefficients are slightly smaller now, whereas other dependencies that Pearson's r did not reveal now seem clearly stronger: Interestingly, the pairwise correlations for ratings (avg, median and per month) and the other popularity metrics (printed, shared, saved) now show much higher values with 0.48 to 0.6 instead of 0.08 to 0.12 (with Pearson's r). We can also see now that there is some dependency between days and shared, which suggests that the number a user's recipes are shared more likely accumulates over time than the other popularity metrics.

The columns printed and printed_per_recipe have a very high pairwise correlation and very similar dependencies with the other variables, which means that we could drop printed_per_recipe for dimensionality reduction, as it does not provide new information. The same is valid for avg_rating and med_rating.

As we have exponential distributions (shown by the histograms and kernel density estimations), we can try logarithmic transformations to normalise the attributes.

How can we use this knowledge about the data distributions?¶

We now know how the different attributes are distributed. This means that we can we can select the recipes that are in the top 5% of the data with respect to their value in each of these attributes. Using that knowledge, we can look for the top 5% recipes regarding their popularity in terms of clicks, votes and favorites. Additionally, when we receive new user data, we can assess their success based on the distributions that we have calculated. Selecting such subsets from a distribution is of course easier if the data resembles a rather normal distribution, as then the position of each data point in relation to the data's mean and percentiles is more easily understandable.

Summary¶

We have found multiple ways to find users that have been successful in the community: by publishing a high amount of recipes or very popular ones. There are simple ways to find users that have collected high popularity metrics in total or with only a few recipes, being quite efficient in that regard. From a business perspective, the overview of efficient users can be used to find recipes that provide a consistently high quality (by only selecting the recipes that come from users that perform well consistently), which is important to achieve a certain quality of service.

One simple way to find outstanding users is to look for outliers in this data. For example, we have shown that the popularity metrics more or less have the same meaning, seeing their pairwise correlation coefficients. However, there will be users that have collected extraordinarily high number of "prints" for their recipes, thus making them an outlier in this comparison. These users most probably will have published more successful recipes than others. Such users can be found looking for data points that lie above the regression line and can be reduced to a few by using margins or an error metric. As an example, users that strongly deviate from the average will have a high mean squared error (MSE). These can be either the very good or very bad users, depending on the direction of the error. Thus, we can easily find the users that are interesting for our business.

Of course, we could just query for the recipes that have the most prints or highest rating, and we would probably find the most popular recipes. However, this extensive statistical analysis helps us to identify users that have been providing good recipes consistently, even if not all of them are among the top recipes regarding their total clicks. This means that our analysis can be very valuable to find recipes with high and consistent quality.

Additionally, we can find users who might not have published successful mainstream recipes (like pancakes), but instead interesting niche foods, e.g. asian vegan cuisine, on a consistent quality level, if we do not only search for the highest clicks, but instead a consistent performance across multiple recipes.

Data preparation¶

We can further improve the data's usability by adding another feature (days passed since publication) or reducing the data to a subset, so computations can go faster. We can also export the dataset in an Excel or csv file, for example, so we can easily integrate the data in other programmes for further evaluation.

Pearson's r shows high pairwise correlation between number_ratings and the popularity metrics (printed, saved, shared), which is understandable. Furthermore, the popularity metrics themselves have relatively high pairwise correlations. It is quite curious that the p-values are all exactly zero, which means that there is a 100% chance that the calculated correlations are correct and might be due to the high number of recipes that are in the dataset.

Spearman's rho shows lower pairwise correlations for the popularity metrics and number_ratings than Pearson's r, but instead reveals other dependencies that avg_rating and days have with the other attributes. As we have seen in the analysis above already, the attribute shared seems to be the most likely one to aggregate over time.

The rating of recipes seem to be most dependent on the number of ratings with a coefficient of 0.77 and the number of saves with a coefficient of 0.64. These coefficients are not high enough to prove a strong dependency, but they might suggest a tendency.

To verify these assumptions we can also take a look at the scatter matrix for this DataFrame:

In [87]:
from pandas.plotting import scatter_matrix
_ = scatter_matrix(numerics, alpha=0.2, figsize=(10, 10), diagonal='kde')

As we have exponential distributions, logarithmic transformations might provide better insight, as the scatter matrix will be more easily interpretable. First, we need a function to add 1 to a Series, so there are no zeros left, which would be problematic when computing the logarithm. Then, we can create a new DataFrame that holds the transformed attributes. It does not make sense to transform all attributes, as that would lead to NaN values in some of the cases. In particular, avg_rating and time_mins contain None values, which lead to NaNs. Neither would it be useful to transform the days attribute, which shows for how many days a recipe has been online. This attribute is of much more use when not transformed, as we can directly interpret its relationship to the other attributes.

In [88]:
# Function for adding 1 to an input:
def add_one(x):
    return x+1

Title analysis¶

What can we learn from the recipe titles? We can either use the titles as they are (which does not provide very valuable results) or split the titles up into single words and perform further steps like word count or generating new features. For this, the data has to be cleaned further.

From over 330,000 recipes, the most frequent name is "Nudelsalat" occurring 112 times, which is interesting but not very significant. Thus, we need to split up multi-word titles and count all words seperately.

While doing this, we also need to clean out characters/symbols and stopwords that do not help in identifying the recipe's content. This will be shown in the next steps:

In [93]:
# Creates a list of single words from a list of multi-word names, removing most-common symbols
nameslist = []
for x in range(len(clickdf)):
    words = clickdf.iloc[x]['name']
    # filter unnecessary characters
    for char in ['"','-','=','!','(',')','.','♥',',',':','~','„','“','/','–','&','+',';','*','☆']:
        words = words.replace(char,'')
    words = words.split(' ',20)  # Split up titles with up to 20 whitespaces
    nameslist.extend(words)
    
# Remove empty elements, which occur when there is a space or symbol at the end of a name
nameslist = list(filter(None, nameslist))

# From each title, pick the two most common words to generate two new columns

toplist1 = []
toplist2 = []

for title in namedf['name']:
    try:
        topword1 = title[0]
        topword2 = title[1]
    except IndexError:
        try: 
            topword1 = title[0]
            topword2 = title[0]
        except IndexError:
            pass
    for word in title:
        if count[word] > count[topword1]:
            topword2 = topword1
            topword1 = word
        if count[word] < count[topword1] & count[word] > count[topword2]:
            topword2 = word
    if topword1 == topword2:
        topword2 = None
    toplist1.append(topword1)
    toplist2.append(topword2)
    
namedf['top1'] = toplist1
namedf['top2'] = toplist2
# namedf.head(10)

One-hot Encoding¶

For attributes that do not have too many distinct values, which repeat many times, one can use one-hot encoding. This technique creates a binary column for every distinct and fills a data point's entry with a one, if it contains the specified value.

For this purpose, we can create a function that encodes specific values from one column in a DataFrame into a new columns, of which each is named after that value.

In [122]:
def encode_onehot(df, col, words):
    def contains_val(l):
        if val in l:
            return 1
        else: return 0

    for val in words:
        df[val] = df[col].apply(contains_val)
In [123]:
# Example usage:
test = pd.DataFrame(['c', ['a', 'b'], ['c', 'a'], ['b', 'a', 'c']])
encode_onehot(test, 0, ['a', 'b', 'c'])
test
Out[123]:

0 c 0 0 1
1 [a, b] 1 1 0
2 [c, a] 1 0 1
3 [b, a, c] 1 1 1

We can use this function to encode the recipe ingredients in the next section. We only need to specify the DataFrame, the column that contains the values to be encoded and a list of selected values to encode, e.g. a list of most common words.

# Cleaning
def clean_ingredients(text):    
    # Remove characters
    for word in text:
        for char in ['"','-','=','!','(',')','.','♥',',',':','~','„','“','/','–','&','+',';','*','☆']:
            if char in word:
                word = word.replace(char,' ') 
    
    # Filter empty list entries
    text = list(filter(None, text)) 
    
    # Filter all stop words defined above
    for stop in stopwords:
        text = list(filter(lambda k: stop != k, text))
    for stop in remove:
        text = list(filter(lambda k: stop != k, text))
    
    # Remove numbers
    text = [t for t in text if not containsNumbers(t)]
    
    # Remove n.B.
    text = [t for t in text if t != 'n.B.']
    
    return text

Conclusion: Explorative Analysis¶

We have used explorative techniques to understand the user and recipe data more deeply and have found interesting dependencies. We can use this knowledge to find the best recipes on the platform much more precisely, as we do not only rely on a single metric, but instead can find users that have published good recipes consistently. Using our scatter matrices we can easily see where to find outliers in the data and some of these outliers will be the users that have performed extraordinarily well.

We have also discovered that a high number of clicks a recipe has collected does not necessarily imply a good quality. Instead, those are most probably the popular mainstream recipes that many people choose because of the dish itself, not necessarily the quality of the recipe. As recipes with many clicks are also more likely to attract more users and gather more clicks, that attribute is distributed exponentially, which is why we might overlook many good recipes if we only judge them by the amount of clicks. To find the actually good recipes that people have enjoyed and decided to come back to for rating them and leaving a comment, we rather should look for recipes with a high amount of favorites (users that have marked that recipe as a favorite).

For selecting a larger number of recipes with consistent quality, we have seen a technique how to select users that have provided good recipes consistently.

The text analysis has provided us insights about:

  • which words are used most frequently in recipe titles, which can hint at the most popular recipes and dishes among authors,
  • which ingredients are used most frequently, thus are most relevant for a large amount of recipes

Additionally, we can use the generated features during further analysis with machine learning algorithms.

2. Trend Analysis¶

This part of the analysis will focus on how the data has changed and evolved over time. For this purpose, we have two different time axes available for usage:

  • the publication date of each recipe
  • monthly snapshots of the data over the last 6 months

Obviously, these two time dimensions do not provide a standard data format for time series analysis, as that would require a large number of uniform timesteps. An example for a standard time series is stock market data, that shows a price for each listing per second, which can be aggregated for the day, week, month, etc. In the case of stock market listings, the price is a value that results from multiple factors and can hold it's value or move up or down. The same goes for data from a temperature sensor, for example.

However, the features in the recipe dataset do not behave like that. Instead, they are either immutable after the recipe's publication (e.g. title and ingredients) or they increase over time by accumulating (e.g. popularity metrics). Only the average rating can change in both directions, but with growing number of rating votes the changes become smaller and a singlevote less significant.

After the start of chefkoch.de in the year 2000, the amount of recipes per year and per month have usually increase (with the exception of a few outliers). This went on until the peak was reached in 2009. The years with the highest number of new recipes are 2007-2009, which could correlate with the financial crisis and the increased unemployment rate in Germany during that time. But to confirm this assumption, the data has to be compared with the respective dataset to validate such hypotheses. During some years, one can see that the fewest recipes were published in spring

As there is not an infinite amount of recipes that can be published, it also seems natural that the number of new recipes has declined over time. This is most probably due to the reason that users are not able to come up with new recipes constantly, but instead share the recipes they now in the beginning and then only share more if they occasionally find new recipes. Additionally, the users might check if a similar version of their recipe has been published already, before publishing their own.

However, there could also just be a trend of decreasing interest in such digital communities, possibly because other websites or apps might be more modern and popular nowadays. For example, the websites Pinterest and Instagram have grown to be a very popular source for food recommendations.

In conclusion, the following effects could be affecting this time series:

  • General popularity peaking in 2009 and decreasing since then (global trend)
  • Increase of new recipes during winter and decrease during spring (local trend)

To verify these assumptions, a more complex time series analysis could be performed. However, from a business perspective this would not create any further value than we could already gain by analysing the histogram, as we now already know enough about the activity on the website.

Clearly, the user community on chefkoch.de seems to prefer cakes and similar sweets, as most favorite recipes are for such dishes. As these are the saved recipes, they could show the user's cooking plans for the next days or weeks, if we assume that users first search for recipes and save them during their research, before cooking them. However, saving usually only happens once, as one user cannot save the same recipe multiple times.

A user might print a recipe rather shortly before cooking it, but this assumption could also be wrong if users rather prefer printing many recipes in advance to create their own recipe collections, independent from when they cook them. Unfortunately, we do not know how users generally behave, but we can at least assume that printing a recipe usually happens at a different time than saving it.

This analysis is of course only a short glimpse and can be expanded to a higher number of recipes per month and over a longer time period. This analysis can help us to find outliers as well, e.g. the rhubarb cake in November, even though rhubarb season is usually during spring. This seems to have been caused by an external effect, which could be an appearance on a TV show or the recipe being featured on the website (kochbar.de recommends "top recipes").

Alternatively, one could also analyse relative increases in popularity, so if a recipe moves from rank 400 to 200 in one month, that is probably a larger increase than another moving from rank 20 to 16.

In conclusion, this trend analysis can help us to find trending recipes for each month quite easily and it also reveals the all-time classics like pancakes and Schnitzel, which only seem to be temporarily moved aside by seasonal competition.

3. Data Mining / Machine Learning¶

The final section of the analysis will present the preparation and application of an exemplary machine learning algorithm on the dataset. Due to the limited frame of this project, only one algorithm can be presented in detail. For this purpose, the method of clustering has been selected.

Clustering can be useful to find similar data points in a dataset that does not have any class labels beforehand, which makes it an unsupervised learning algorithm. This means that we can use clustering to group the recipes in clusters that contain similar dishes.

There are many different clustering algorithms that work after different principles and thus are suited of different types of data, depending on the dataset's size, shape and other properties.

Visualisation with t-SNE¶

t-SNE is a recently developed and quite popular method for projecting highly dimensional data onto a two- or three-dimensional space for visualisation purposes. This method also helps in distinguishing clusters. As this is a significant dimensionality reduction, using this process before clustering the data points can aid in reducing computation time greatly. One feature that is suited very well for t-SNE is the word vector that we have created for the top1 word in each recipe's title. As a visualisation needs to be simple and clear, we will only use a small subset of data in during this process.

from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

def tsne_plot(model, perplexity):
    "Creates and TSNE model and plots it"
    labels = []
    tokens = []

    for word in top100_words:
        tokens.append(model[word])
        labels.append(word)
    
    tsne_model = TSNE(perplexity=perplexity, n_components=2, init='pca', n_iter=5000, random_state=23)
    new_values = tsne_model.fit_transform(tokens)

    x = []
    y = []
    for value in new_values:
        x.append(value[0])
        y.append(value[1])
        
    Z = []
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10)) 
    for i in range(len(x)):
        Z.append([x[i], y[i]])
        plt.scatter(x[i],y[i])
        plt.annotate(labels[i],
                     xy=(x[i], y[i]),
                     xytext=(5, 2),
                     textcoords='offset points',
                     ha='right',
                     va='bottom')
    plt.show()
    
    return Z

The t-SNE visualisation shows how well similar words are placed close to each other. There are many examples for which this has worked very well, for example fruits and dessert, salad, vegetables, spices, noodles and rice, fish or chicken. There is also something quite interesting in the case of pork meat: while filet and schnitzel are placed close to chicken and fish, ham and bacon lie much closer to cheese, lasagne and vegetables.

This shows that, even in the two-dimensional space, the word embeddings of the most common word in a recipe's title can be used to cluster it with similar recipes. In the 100-dimensional space, such clusterings will probably be even more accurate.

Clustering with DBSCAN¶

As we have seen in the t-SNE visualisation, points with similar words are more dense. However, they are not all placed in globular shape, but can instead form a line or a circle. Thus, we need to choose a clustering algorithm that is density-based. DBSCAN is a common density-based clustering algorithm.

For simplicity and comparability, we will perform a clustering on the vectors that were created by t-SNE, so the formed clusters can directly be compared with the respective plot from above.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Black removed and is used for noise instead.
n_clusters_ = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
unique_labels = set(labels)
colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(each)
          for each in np.linspace(0, 1, len(unique_labels))]

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
for k, col in zip(unique_labels, colors):
    if k == -1:
        # Black used for noise.
        col = [0, 0, 0, 1]

    class_member_mask = (labels == k)

    xy = X[class_member_mask & core_samples_mask]
    plt.plot(xy[:, 0], xy[:, 1], 'o', markerfacecolor=tuple(col),
             markeredgecolor='k', markersize=14)

    xy = X[class_member_mask & ~core_samples_mask]
    plt.plot(xy[:, 0], xy[:, 1], 'o', markerfacecolor=tuple(col),
             markeredgecolor='k', markersize=6)

plt.title('Estimated number of clusters: %d' % n_clusters_)
plt.show()

Summary Data Mining¶

We have seen how the data can be transformed by dimensionality reduction to create two-dimensional presentations that can be plotted well. Additionally, the results from clustering with DBSCAN have shown that even the data with reduced dimensions can be clustered very accurately into recipe categories.

For an alternative approach to clustering, the ingredients could be used as well. By increasing the dimensionality of the dataset before applying t-SNE (i.e. one-hot encoding with 1,000 ingredients or more, for example), the representation would probably reach a higher accuracy. However, as this is an unsupervised learning problem, we cannot perform an automatic accuracy testing, but we can see by looking at the results that the chosen algorithms have worked very well.

When applying these techniques to categorise all recipes in the dataset, it will be better to use more than just the 100 most frequent words, of course. Then, the t-SNE visualisation will most probably not be readable anymore, but the results from clustering can then be applied to many different recipes and work very well.
